Die Verlierer bleiben Herausforderer
HARARE: Vor den Präsidentschaftswahlen in diesem Monat war ich überzeugt davon, dass Unregelmäßigkeiten bei den Wahlen ernsthafte Konsequenzen in Simbabwe selbst und im ganzen südlichen Afrika hätten.
Trotz der Schatten von Krieg und Terrorismus rief ich zu fairen und freien Wahlen auf.
Die Menschen von Simbabwe haben sie nicht bekommen.
Stattdessen haben sie Terror erhalten.
In the two years that led to the presidential elections, the people of Zimbabwe have been victims of intimidation, harassment and threats by the party of Robert Mugabe, the African National Union - Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF), whose program is state-subsidized terrorism.
ZANU terrorism is the work of crooked elements among the veterans from Zimbabwe's independence war two decades ago, the government militias and young men, all of whom are supported by the police.
The consequence of intimidation and violence was that my party, the Movement for Democratic Change (MDC), did not reach the electorate in large parts, particularly in the rural areas.
In addition, the government of my opponent, President Mugabe, has effectively disempowered hundreds of thousands of voters in the cities, particularly in the capital Harare and in Chitungwiza.
As there were not enough polling stations overall, in my opinion, more than 360,000 people stood in line in Harare and Chitungwiza alone, without being able to cast their ballot papers into the ballot boxes.
I continue to doubt the legitimacy of the election results, because Mugabe's militias prevented the MDC from placing election observers in 52% of rural polling stations.
Towards the end of the voting, our party had observers missing at 6 out of 10 polling stations in the countryside.
This means that Mugabe's supporters were able to impose their will in these polling stations.
We are currently compiling a comprehensive list of all the polling stations that were only controlled by ZANU supporters.
In our preliminary investigations, even at this early stage, a pattern has emerged: in these polling stations, the majority of votes were cast for Mugabe.
Given the overwhelming evidence, I cannot accept the results of the presidential elections, from which the incumbent president Robert Mugabe emerged as the winner with 56% of the 3 million votes cast.
The official results do not reflect the true will of the people of Zimbabwe and are in their eyes illegitimate.
The people of Zimbabwe had their right to elect a president of their choice freely and democratically taken away.
The struggle over the election results is a political matter that must be resolved politically.
Food and fuel are scarce, jobs are being lost, and inflation is over 100%.
The people of Zimbabwe were brave and resolute and have deserved to have this acknowledged.
Perhaps it is not too late for this.
I am writing this text in sorrow, because Mugabe's regime still ignores the will of the people.
Whatever happens, I will stand by the people as a loyal servant and walk the path with them to the end.
Perhaps the government will arrest me.
Ich wurde ja auch schon vor den Wahlen wegen Hochverrats verhaftet.
Im schlimmsten Fall wollen sie mich sogar töten.
Aber die Regierung wird den Willen des Volkes, seine Rechte und seine Macht zurückzufordern, nie brechen können.
Es liegt in unserer Hand, einen demokratischen Wandel zu vollziehen.
In den kommenden Tagen werden wir Momente der Angst erleben, aber wir dürfen nicht zulassen, dass uns die Verzweiflung übermannt.
The political change is unstoppable.
But we must be ready to pay a high price for our freedom.
President Mugabe and his henchmen fear the people, and we have heard that they will do everything to kill the messenger.
If it comes to that, I ask the people of Zimbabwe only to remain strong and to finish what we have started together.
There are many heroes in the people of Zimbabwe - heroes who waited for hours to vote, heroes who were not allowed to leave.
They are the heroes of a new Zimbabwe, whose voice must be heard around the world.
We have walked a very rocky path together to achieve a democratic change in our country.
In the history of humanity, a people have rarely endured such violence and yet managed to preserve kindness and exuberance.
I notice that the population of Zimbabwe is impatient.
I understand that.
But in order for there to be a political process, they must be patient and wait.
They cannot simply leave these elections as they are, but they must also not fall for Mugabe's provocation and resort to violence.
The people of Zimbabwe want change, in the constitution, in the legal system, legitimate change, and they will achieve it, despite all the obstacles.
We know that we are not standing alone.
We know that in all of Africa, elections are rigged.
In most African countries, it seems that irregularities, fraud, and deception in elections are the norm.
In Africa, there is always some crisis related to elections somewhere.
It is sad, but the entire continent is plagued by governments that resort to unfair means when it is time to grant people their voting rights.
But those who want something different can hope.
Zimbabwe's struggle is not yet over.
Noch ist Zeit, aus unserer Erfahrung die Lehren für Afrika und die Welt zu ziehen.
My people are in the hour of their greatest need.
I swear not to abandon them.
